data.content:
`SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` was deprecated in Android API 30 and is no longer honored in .NET 10. There are two main replacements:

---

### Option 1 — Use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (simplest)

MAUI 8+ has a built-in auto-scroll manager enabled by default. Wrap your page content in a `ScrollView` and it should just work:

```xml
<ScrollView>
  <Grid RowDefinitions="*,Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ... />
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1">
      <Entry Placeholder="Message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
      <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
  </Grid>
</ScrollView>
```

If it's misbehaving, you can toggle it per-page:

```csharp
KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect();  // disable
KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Connect();     // re-enable
```

---

### Option 2 — React to keyboard insets manually (more control)

Use the modern Android `WindowInsets` API via a platform-specific handler to add bottom padding when the keyboard opens:

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs or your page's OnAppearing
#if ANDROID
Microsoft.Maui.ApplicationModel.Platform.CurrentActivity?
    .Window?.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false);
#endif
```

Then in `Platforms/Android/`, create a helper:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

public static class KeyboardInsetHelper
{
    public static void Apply(View rootView, View targetView)
    {
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new InsetListener(targetView));
    }

    private class InsetListener(View target) : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);

            target.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);
            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

Wire it up in your page:

```csharp
protected override void OnAppearing()
{
    base.OnAppearing();
#if ANDROID
    var activity = Platform.CurrentActivity;
    var rootView = activity?.Window?.DecorView?.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content);
    if (rootView != null)
        KeyboardInsetHelper.Apply(rootView, rootView);
#endif
}
```

---

**TL;DR:** Try Option 1 first — just ensure your layout is inside a `ScrollView`. If you need pixel-precise control (common in chat UIs), go with Option 2 and the `WindowInsets` API, which is the modern Android replacement for `AdjustResize`.
